         <abstract>
            <p>The maximal modulus of an algebraic integer is the absolute value of its largest conjugate. We compute the minimum of the maximal modulus of all algebraic integers of degree $d$ which are not roots of unity, for $d$ at most 12. The computations suggest that the minimum is never attained for a reciprocal algebraic integer. The truth of this conjecture would show that the conjecture of Schinzel and Zassenhaus follows from a theorem of Smyth. We further test our conjecture by computing the minimum of the maximal modulus of all reciprocal algebraic integers of degree $d$ which are not roots of unity, for $d$ at most 16. Our computations strongly suggest that the best constant in the conjecture of Schinzel and Zassenhaus is $1.5 \log \theta_0$, where $\theta_0$ is the smallest P.V. number. They also shed some light on a recent conjecture of Lind concerning the Perron numbers.</p>
          </abstract>
